<DOC><DOCNO> AP880722-0222 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1946EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-22 0469</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0482</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Rain Falls On Eastern North Carolina</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms dumped heavy rain over parts of the South onFriday, soaking parched crops and causing some flooding, and rainalso fell on parts of the drought-stricken Midwest.   Eastern North Carolina got heavy rain from a cluster of nearlystationary thunderstorms that were part of a large area of slowlymoving showers and thunderstorms that formed ahead of a cold frontalong the Atlantic Coast states.   Wilmington, N.C., got a record 6.49 inches of rain for the date,well over the former record of 3.88 inches set in 1877.   The water flooded street drains in downtown Wilmington, stallingcars and tying up traffic.   Rain also was heavy over other areas of eastern North Carolina,where New Bern got 1.60 inches and 1.31 inches fell on Jacksonville.   But rainfall in North Carolina's southern and central Piedmontis running about 8 inches below normal for the year, while themountains would need 14 inches in a short period to eliminate thedrought, experts said.   In southern Mississippi, Columbia got 1.5 inches of rain andhalf-inch diameter hail.   Mobile, Ala., got more than an inch of rain within 25 minutesand Huntsville got over half an inch within one hour.   In northeastern Florida, more than 2{ inches of rain wasreported within one hour south of Lake City.   In the Midwest, widely scattered thunderstorms carried brieflyheavy rain over northern Indiana, western Ohio and Lower Michigan,where some Kalamazoo streets were reported flooded, the NationalWeather Service said.   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered oversouthern Texas, southeastern Louisiana, southern Georgia, easternsections of the Atlantic Coast states and sections of Kentucky.   Widely scattered thunderstorms developed over the mountain anddesert regions of southern California and southern Nevada andisolated rainshowers were over central Oklahoma.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 109 at Gila Bend, Ariz. The lowFriday morning was 34 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.   For Saturday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastover the Atlantic Coast states, the eastern Gulf Coast region,Alabama and Florida. Numerous showers were forecast oversoutheastern Maine. Scattered showers and thunderstorms also wereforecast over the mountains and desert regions of southernCalifornia.   High in the 70s were predicted over New England, the northernand central Appalachians and eastern Ohio; in the 70s and low 80sover northwestern Washington state and along the California coast;in the 80s over the Great Lakes states, the Ohio and Tennesseevalleys, the middle Mississippi Valley, the southern Appalachians,the southern and central Atlantic Coast states except Florida, andAlabama; between 100 and 110 over the desert Southwest and sectionsof the Great Basin; and in the 90s over the remainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>